04350nam a22007935i 9780231553209DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20212020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315532097 a10.7312/fran199602doi  a(DE-B1597)566465  a(OCoLC)1237404437  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHV4708 7aPHI0050002bisacsh1 aFrancione, Gary, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhy Veganism Matters :bThe Moral Value of Animals /cGary Francione. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2021] 4c©2020  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical Perspectives on Animals: Theory, Culture, Science and Law00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 Our Conventional Wisdom — Animals as Quasi- Persons -- t2 Two Contemporary Approaches to Animal Personhood -- t3 Animals as Persons—a Matter of Sentience Alone -- t4 The Right Not to Be Property -- t5 Veganism as a Moral Imperative -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tReference/Study Guide0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMost people care about animals, but only a tiny fraction are vegan. The rest often think of veganism as an extreme position. They certainly do not believe that they have a moral obligation to become vegan.Gary L. Francione—the leading and most provocative scholar of animal rights theory and law—demonstrates that veganism is a moral imperative and a matter of justice. He shows that there is a contradiction in thinking that animals matter morally if one is also not vegan, and he explains why this belief should logically lead all who hold it to veganism. Francione dismantles the conventional wisdom that it is acceptable to use and kill animals as long as we do so “humanely.” He argues that if animals matter morally, they must have the right not to be used as property. That means that we cannot eat them, wear them, use them, or otherwise treat them as resources or commodities.Why Veganism Matters presents the case for the personhood of nonhuman animals and for veganism in a clear and accessible way that does not require any philosophical or legal background. This book offers a persuasive and powerful argument for all readers who care about animals but are not sure whether they have a moral obligation to be vegan.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aAnimal rights. 0aAnimal welfare-Moral and ethical aspects. 0aAnimal welfare. 0aVeganismxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aVeganism. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh  aanimal abolition.  aanimal abolitionist movement.  aanimal liberation.  aanimal welfare.  aethics.  avegan.  aveganism.  avegetarianism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311071097740uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/fran1996040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231553209423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231553209/original  a978-3-11-071097-7  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK